fields.name: general
fields.category_description: Our most popular course. You will recieve expert tuition on all language skills from reading, writing, grammar and listening. The main focus however is always speaking and you will have plenty of opportunity to practise your spoken English with fellow studetns and your teacher.

fields.name: business
fields.category_description: If you need to improve your English to help further your career thiese are the courses for you. You will receive expert tution in all four lanaguage skills with an emphasis on email writing and presentation skills. As well as reading and understadning complex articles and work-related vocabulary.

fields.name: academic
fields.category_description: We offer specific courses for the main English Language exams. By far our most popular is IELTS preparatio which will get you ready to succeed in the IELTS exam no matter your previous experience. We also teach the FCE and CAE Cambridge exams and TOEFL.

fields.name: under_16s
fields.category_description: We offer multiple under 16's courses at the school from 5 years and up. Students will recieve fun and informative lessons that are level and age based and include outings to museums in the city center.

fields.name: ge_full_time
fields.course_description: The most comprehensive way to improve your English. Classes will focus on Speaking primarily, however all other language skills will be taught to help your fluency, grammatical accuracy and above all confidence in using English. You will study with the same teacher each day and have weekly progress tests to check that you are improving.

fields.name: ge_part_time
fields.course_description: The most comprehensive way to improve your English if you don't have the time to spare for a more intensive course. Classes will focus on Speaking primarily, however all other language skills will be taught to help your fluency, grammatical accuracy and above all confidence in using English. You will study with the same teacher each day and have weekly progress tests to check that you are improving.

fields.name: ielts_intensive
fields.course_description: The most comprehensive way to study for the IELTS exam . You will practice all four parts of the exam with an experienced IELTS specialist teacher. The course includes mock exams and detailed feedback on your projected IELTS level. If you need to achieve a band 6.5 or above it is recommended you study for at least 8 weeks.

fields.post_content:
The kerer (Hemiphaga novaeseelandiae) or New Zealand pigeon is a species of pigeon native to New Zealand. Johann Friedrich Gmelin described the bird in 1789 as a large, conspicuous pigeon up to 50 cm (20 in) in length and 550850 g (1930 oz) in weight, with a white breast and iridescent greenblue plumage. Two subspecies have been recognised; the secondthe Norfolk pigeon of Norfolk Islandbecame extinct in the early 20th century. Kerer pairs are monogamous, breeding over successive seasons and remaining together when not breeding. They construct nests with twigs in trees, with a single egg clutch.

Found in a variety of habitats across the country, the kerer feeds mainly on fruits, as well as leaves, buds and flowers. Although widespread in both forest and urban habitats, its numbers have declined significantly since European colonisation and the arrival of invasive mammals such as rats, stoats and possums. However, the results of nationwide bird surveys indicate that there has been a significant recovery in the population of kerer in suburban areas. Despite this, as of 2021, the IUCN Red List classifies the species as "near threatened", while the Department of Conservation (DOC) classifies kerer as "not threatened" but conservation dependent.
Considered a taonga (cultural treasure) to the Mori people, the kerer was historically a major food source in Mori culture. However, due to the previous decline in its population, hunting is illegal. Customary use of kerer is restricted to the use of feathers and bones obtained from dead birds collected by DOC. This issue has received significant public and political attention, as some people argue that bans on kerer hunting are detrimental to Mori traditions. In 2018, the kerer was designated Bird of the Year by the New Zealand organisation Forest & Bird, and in 2019, the exoplanet HD 137388 b was renamed Kerer in its honour.
